        "paragraphs": [
            "Quadratic Polynomial :",
            "A polynomial of second degree is caled a quadratic polynomial.",
            "Eg. $@\"x^2 - 3\"@$",
            "$@\"4x^2 - 5x + 6.\"@$",
            "Zeros of a Quadratic polynomial :",
            "The value of x in a polynomial for which polynomial function becomes zero, is called zero(s) of the given polynomial.",
            "If 'a' is a zero of the polynomial $@\"f(x)\\;then\\;f(a) = 0. \"@$",
            "Quadratic Equation :",
            "An equation of degree 2 is a quadratic equation.",
            "Eg : $@\"2x^2 -4x+ 7 =0 \"@$",
            "$@\"ax^2 + bx + c = 0\"@$",
            "Nature of the Roots of the equation $@\" ax^2 + bx+ c = 0\"@$",
            "Discriminent : $@\" D = b^2 -4ac\"@$",
            "(i) If D&gt;O - unequal and real roots",
            "(ii) If D-O - equal and real roots",
            "(iii) If D &lt; O - No real roots.",
            "Roots of the equation $@\"ax^2 + bx+ c = 0\"@$ are",
            "$@\"\\alpha = {{'\\frac{-b+\\sqrtB}{2a}'}}\\;and\\;\\beta ={{'\\frac{-b-\\sqrtB}{2a}'}} \"@$",
            "Sum of the roots $@\"\\alpha+ \\beta = {{'\\frac{-b}{a}'}}\"@$",
            "Product of the roots $@\"\\alpha \\beta = {{'\\frac{c}{a}'}}\"@$",
            "Equal roots $@\"\\alpha = \\beta = {{'\\frac{-b}{2a}'}}\"@$",
            "If $@\"\\alpha\\;and\\;\\beta\"@$ are the roots of the equation then the",
            "equation can be written as",
            "$@\"x^2 - x(sum\\;of\\;the\\;roots)+(product\\;of\\;the\\;roots)=0\"@$ (or)",
            "$@\"x^2-x(\\alpha + \\beta)+ \\alpha \\beta =0\"@$",
            "lmportant Formulae :",
            "$@\"\\alpha^2 + \\beta^2 = (\\alpha+\\beta)^2 - 2\\alpha \\beta\"@$",
            "$@\"(\\alpha - \\beta)^2 = (\\alpha+\\beta)^2 - 4\\alpha \\beta\"@$",
            "$@\"\\alpha^4 + \\beta^4 =\\;[(\\alpha+\\beta)^2 -2\\alpha \\beta]^2 -2 \\alpha^2 \\beta^2\"@$",
            "$@\"\\alpha^5 + \\beta^5 =\\; (\\alpha^3+\\beta^3)\\;(\\alpha^2+\\beta^2) - \\alpha^2 \\beta^2 (\\alpha+\\beta)\"@$"
        ]
    }
